=3D"CDt4Ke zfr3Q">When doing a series of mathematical operations, you shoul=
d <em>not</em> round at each individual step. You should keep track of the =
number of significant figures produced at each step, then round at the end.=
</p><p id=3D"h.p_ID_74" class=3D"CDt4Ke zfr3Q">For example: (30.62 =C3=B7 2=
.0) + 0.4 =3D 16</p><p id=3D"h.p_ID_76" class=3D"CDt4Ke zfr3Q">To arrive at=
 this answer, you would first analyze each step...</p><p id=3D"h.p_ID_78" c=
lass=3D"CDt4Ke zfr3Q">1) 30.62 =C3=B7 2.0 =3D 15.31. If rounded, the result=
 would have only have two significant figures, and thus no digits after the=
 decimal point.</p><p id=3D"h.p_ID_80" class=3D"CDt4Ke zfr3Q">2) Take the <=
em>unrounded</em> value, 15.31, and add 0.4. 15.31 + 0.4 =3D 15.71. From st=
ep 1, we know the result should have no digits after the decimal point, and=
 so we round to the ones place, 15.71 =E2=89=88 16.</p><p id=3D"h.p_ID_82" =
class=3D"CDt4Ke zfr3Q">You may be wondering, "Why is 16 a better answer tha=
n 15.71? Isn't the number more accurate with more digits?". But remember, t=
he original values (30.62, 2.0, and 0.4) each have some degree of error in =
them (since nearly everything in science is a measurement). If we report th=
e answer as 15.71, we imply that we <em>know</em> it's between 15.70 and 15=
.72, and that is simply not true. The accumulated error puts the ones place=
 in doubt, so by reporting the answer as 16 we imply that it's roughly betw=
een 15 and 17.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></s=
